Here is the sample C++ code that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file.

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    string filename, word;
    int count = 0;

    cout << "Enter filename: ";
    getline(cin, filename);

    cout << "Enter word to count: ";
    cin >> word;

    ifstream inputFile(filename);
    if (inputFile.is_open()) {
        string line;
        while (getline(inputFile, line)) {
            size_t found = line.find(word);
            while (found != string::npos) {
                count++;
                found = line.find(word, found + 1);
            }
        }
        inputFile.close();
        cout << "Number of occurrences of \"" << word << "\" in " << filename << " is " << count << endl;
    } else {
        cout << "Unable to open file." << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, `string` and `fstream` libraries are used to read the text file and count the word occurrences. The user is prompted to enter the filename and the word to count. 

The program opens the file and reads it line by line using the `getline()` function. It then checks for occurrences of the specified word in each line using the `find()` function. If the word is found, the count is incremented. The function `npos` is used to specify the end of the string when searching for the word.

Once the entire file has been read, the program output the number of occurrences of the specified word.

